---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const releaseUrl = "https://github.com/ComputelessComputer/openbird/releases/latest";
const sourceUrl = "https://github.com/ComputelessComputer/openbird";

const captures = [
  "frontmost app and bundle ID",
  "window title",
  "browser tab URL when available",
  "visible text from the active window accessibility tree",
  "start and end timestamps",
];

const noCapture = [
  "raw key events",
  "clipboard contents",
  "passwords",
  "secure text fields",
  "hidden or minimized windows",
  "automatic screenshots",
];

const questions = [
  "What did I do today?",
  "What was I working on around 3pm?",
  "Which project took most of my attention?",
  "What tabs, apps, or docs was I using during that block?",
];

const models = [
  "Ollama",
  "LM Studio",
  "other OpenAI-compatible endpoints",
];
---

<BaseLayout description="Openbird is a local-first macOS activity journal. It captures your current work context on your Mac, stores that data locally, and turns it into a daily review and follow-up chat.">
  <main class="page">
    <header>
      <p><strong>Openbird</strong></p>
      <p class="muted">Local-first macOS activity journal.</p>
      <nav aria-label="Page">
        <ul>
          <li><a href="#what-it-does">What it does</a></li>
          <li><a href="#privacy">Privacy</a></li>
          <li><a href="#models">Models</a></li>
          <li><a href="#install">Install</a></li>
          <li><a href={sourceUrl}>GitHub</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </header>

    <hr />

    <section>
      <h1>Software that watches your day should not be a black box.</h1>
      <p>
        Openbird captures your current work context on your Mac, stores that data locally, and turns it
        into a daily review and follow-up chat.
      </p>
      <p>
        No account is required. No backend is required. The point is that if software can see this much
        of your day, you should be able to inspect it, control it, and delete it.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href={releaseUrl}>Download the latest release</a>
        {" · "}
        <a href={sourceUrl}>Read the source code</a>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="what-it-does">
      <h2>What Openbird Does</h2>
      <p>
        Openbird watches the frontmost app and window, builds a local timeline of your day, and uses
        that log to generate:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>a daily review with time blocks, highlights, and a short narrative</li>
        <li>follow-up chat scoped to your local activity data</li>
        <li>citations back to the underlying apps, windows, URLs, and timestamps</li>
      </ul>
      <p>It is meant to answer questions like:</p>
      <ul>
        {questions.map((question) => (
          <li>{question}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What This Looks Like</h2>
      <pre>09:08  Xcode         reviewed timeline UI and journal flow
11:24  Safari        compared Ollama and LM Studio endpoints
14:37  Notes         prepared follow-up questions from the local log

Review ready.
Sources linked.
Stored locally on your Mac.</pre>
    </section>

    <section id="privacy">
      <h2>Privacy Boundary</h2>
      <p>Openbird is intentionally conservative.</p>

      <h3>Openbird captures</h3>
      <ul>
        {captures.map((item) => (
          <li>{item}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <h3>Openbird does not capture</h3>
      <ul>
        {noCapture.map((item) => (
          <li>{item}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>

      <p>
        You can also pause capture, exclude apps, exclude domains, inspect the raw log used for
        generation, and delete the last hour, the last day, or everything.
      </p>

      <p class="small muted">
        Local storage path: <code>~/Library/Application Support/Openbird/openbird.sqlite</code>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="models">
      <h2>Bring Your Own Model</h2>
      <p>Openbird supports local-first BYOK out of the box.</p>
      <ul>
        {models.map((model) => (
          <li>{model}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
      <p>You can run fully offline if your model is local.</p>
      <p class="small muted">
        Default local endpoints:
        <br />
        Ollama: <code>http://127.0.0.1:11434/v1</code>
        <br />
        LM Studio: <code>http://127.0.0.1:1234/v1</code>
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="install">
      <h2>Install</h2>
      <p>Current release target: macOS 14+ on Apple Silicon.</p>
      <ol>
        <li><a href={releaseUrl}>Download the latest release</a>.</li>
        <li>Open the DMG and drag <code>Openbird.app</code> into Applications.</li>
        <li>Launch the app and grant Accessibility permission when prompted.</li>
        <li>Choose an Ollama or LM Studio preset in Settings.</li>
        <li>Generate your first review from the Today screen.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Open Source</h2>
      <p>
        Open source is not a branding choice here. It is part of the product. When software observes
        your work, transparency matters.
      </p>
      <p>
        You should be able to inspect how it captures data, where it stores it, what it excludes, and
        which model receives your prompts.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <footer>
      <p class="small">
        Openbird is a local-first macOS activity journal.
        <a href={releaseUrl}>Latest release</a>.
        <a href={sourceUrl}>Source code</a>.
      </p>
    </footer>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
